[1] Cholera - Mexico (Hidalgo State)
Date: Mon 28 Jul 2014
Source: AM de Querataro [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
http://amqueretaro.com/2014/07/suman-11-casos-de-colera-en-hidalgo/.html


Cholera has been detected in 3 municipalities of Hidalgo; with the confirmation by health authorities in the State of 2 new cases, now in the municipality of Mixquiahuala, there are now 11 sick people confirmed.

In a press conference, Concepcion Carmona Ramos, Director of Policy and Strategies in Public Health, reported that the individuals are 2 older adults belonging to the same family.

"Hidalgo is the only State that has reported cases of cholera; that is why it is important to strengthen preventive measures," she said.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Recently 2 cases of the infection were also reported in Veracruz State. A map of Mexico showing the locations of the states of Veracruz and Hidalgo can be found at http://www.ezilon.com/maps/images/northamerica/political-map-of-Mexico.gif. A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map of Mexico is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2643450,496.

In a recently released report (MMWR Morb Mortal Wkly Rep 2014; 63(25); 552-3 http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm6325a5.htm?s_cid=mm6325a5_w), during 19 Sep 2013-15 Dec 2013, a total of 175 cases of cholera were confirmed in La Huasteca (159 in Hidalgo, 14 in Veracruz, and 2 in San Luis Potosi). These cases and those of 2013 occurred in La Huasteca area (http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_Huasteca), a geographical and cultural region located in Mexico along the Gulf of Mexico that includes parts of the states of Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Puebla, Hidalgo, San Luis Potosi, Queretaro, and Guanajuato. It is roughly defined as the area in which the Huastec people had influence when their civilization was at its height in the Mesoamerican period. Today, the Huastecs occupy only a fraction of this region, with the Nahua people now the most numerous indigenous group. - Mod.LL]

******
[2] Cholera - Nigeria (Borno State) refugee camps
Date: Tue 29 Jul 2014
Source: Daily Post [edited]
http://dailypost.ng/2014/07/29/boko-haram-cholera-hits-refugee-camp-borno/


Cholera has hit the 2 camps in Biu Local Government Area of Borno state, where refugees who fled their homes in Damboa Local Government area of the state as a result of attacks by the Islamic sect, Boko Haram are taking shelter.

DailyPost learned that the 2 camps housing over 11 000 refugees need immediate medical intervention as a result of the spread of the disease. According to reports in Biu, the camps have started witnessing a number of victims of cholera.

Mallam Habu Isa, a resident of Biu told DailyPost that the camp at one of the Primary Schools in Biu and the one at Government Girls' Secondary School in Biu town were begging for immediate assistance from the Borno State Government. He said that some medical personnel from Maiduguri, were at the camps, lamenting that they left after 2 days, but the disease has continued to affect the 2 camps.

[Byline: Maina Maina]

